### Constructors

A constructor is a special member function that is automatically called when an object is created. It has the same name as the class and no return type.

---

### Default Constructor

```cpp
class Car {
public:
  Car() {  // Default constructor
    brand = "Unknown";
    year = 0;
  }
private:
  string brand;
  int year;
};
```

---

### Parameterized Constructor

```cpp
class Car {
public:
  Car(string b, int y) {  // Parameterized constructor
    brand = b;
    year = y;
  }
private:
  string brand;
  int year;
};

Car myCar("Toyota", 2022);
```

---

### Constructor Initialization List

```cpp
class Car {
public:
  Car(string b, int y) : brand(b), year(y) {
    // Body is optional
  }
private:
  string brand;
  int year;
};
```

---

### Copy Constructor

```cpp
class Car {
public:
  Car(const Car& other) : brand(other.brand), year(other.year) {
    cout << "Copy constructor called";
  }
};

Car car2(car1);  // Copy constructor
```

---

### Move Constructor (C++11)

```cpp
class Car {
public:
  Car(Car&& other) noexcept
    : brand(std::move(other.brand)), year(other.year) {
    other.year = 0;
  }
};
```

---

### Constructor Overloading

```cpp
class Car {
public:
  Car() : Car("Unknown", 0) {}         // Delegating to below
  Car(string b, int y) : brand(b), year(y) {}
};
```

---

> **Key Point:** Always use initialization lists instead of assignment in constructors. They are more efficient and necessary for initializing const and reference members.

